{"title_page": "Johnny Christopher", "text_new": "'''John Lee Christopher Jr'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secondhandsongs.com/artist/3178|title=Songs written by Johnny Christopher {{!}} SecondHandSongs|website=secondhandsongs.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> (born 1943 in [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jones|first=Roben|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=t6fXPucJupIC&pg=PR18&lpg=PR18&dq=johnny+christopher+songwriter+-carson&source=bl&ots=KswK0fzXzd&sig=ACfU3U3gSiq5NOBSmRxSuTSxvqVmA1mQCQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiovYGAsfXoAhVVB50JHQ6kBtsQ6AEwBHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=johnny%20christopher%20songwriter%20-carson&f=false|title=Memphis Boys: The Story of American Studios|date=2010-11-12|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|isbn=978-1-60473-402-7|language=en}}</ref>) is an American singer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/395167-Johnny-Christopher|title=Johnny Christopher|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, guitarist, session musician and [[songwriter]]. \n\n==Background==\nChristopher\u2019s singles included \u201c(She's A) Girl Of Many Colors / The Teacher And The Pet\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Johnny-Christopher-Shes-Colors-Teacher/dp/B0763CX5LJ|title=(She's A) Girl Of Many Colors / The Teacher And The Pet|website=www.amazon.ca|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> (1968) and \u201cLove Stuff\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MYh_DiL3cNg|title=LOVE STUFF ~ JOHNNY CHRISTOPHER|last=|first=|date=2013-10-02|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> (1972). As a songwriter, he wrote \u201d[[Mama Liked the Roses]]\" for [[Elvis Presley]] and co-wrote \"[[Always on My Mind]]\" with [[Mark James (songwriter)|Mark James]] and [[Wayne Carson]], a song first recorded by [[B.J. Thomas]] in 1970. [[Gwen McCrae]] also recorded the song as did [[Brenda Lee]] in 1972. The song has been covered by several well-known artists including Elvis Presley, [[John Wesley Ryles]] and [[the Pet Shop Boys]]. \n\nHe also co-wrote the 1974 song \"[[If You Talk in Your Sleep]]\" for Elvis Presley with [[Red West]].\n\nFor [[Willie Nelson]]'s 1982 cover, Christopher, James, and Carson won [[1983 Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Country Song|Best Country Song]], 10 years after its original release.<ref>{{cite book|title=Memphis Boys: The Story of American Studios|last=Jones|first=Roben|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|year=2010|url=https://archive.org/details/memphisboysstory00jone|url-access=registration|quote=johnny christopher always on my mind.|page=[https://archive.org/details/memphisboysstory00jone/page/337 337]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nP3QCgBwEJ4C&pg=PT232&lpg=PT232&dq=johnny+christopher+always+on+my+mind&source=bl&ots=QL7DQZddci&sig=1DTBhi0m7zBVl9IamadDYvqFvCk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jJziVLKnKcX_gwTc0oHgBQ&ved=0CEMQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=johnny%20christopher%20always%20on%20my%20mind&f=false|title=Stalking the Red Headed Straonger|first=Randy|last=Poe|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, he was no longer in the music industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sirshambling.com/artists_2012/C/artie_christopher/index.php|title=ARTIE CHRISTOPHER : Sir Shambling\u2019s Deep Soul Heaven|website=www.sirshambling.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{songwriter-stub}}\n\n{{Grammy Award for Song of the Year 1980s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Christopher, Johnny}}\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Song of the Year]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Lee Christopher Jr'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secondhandsongs.com/artist/3178|title=Songs written by Johnny Christopher {{!}} SecondHandSongs|website=secondha