y Awards|Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Country Song|Best Country Song]], 10 years after its original release.<ref>{{cite book|title=Memphis Boys: The Story of American Studios|last=Jones|first=Roben|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|year=2010|url=https://archive.org/details/memphisboysstory00jone|url-access=registration|quote=johnny christopher always on my mind.|page=[https://archive.org/details/memphisboysstory00jone/page/337 337]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nP3QCgBwEJ4C&pg=PT232&lpg=PT232&dq=johnny+christopher+always+on+my+mind&source=bl&ots=QL7DQZddci&sig=1DTBhi0m7zBVl9IamadDYvqFvCk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jJziVLKnKcX_gwTc0oHgBQ&ved=0CEMQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=johnny%20christopher%20always%20on%20my%20mind&f=false|title=Stalking the Red Headed Straonger|first=Randy|last=Poe|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, he was no longer in the music industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sirshambling.com/artists_2012/C/artie_christopher/index.php|title=ARTIE CHRISTOPHER : Sir Shambling\u2019s Deep Soul Heaven|website=www.sirshambling.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{songwriter-stub}}\n\n{{Grammy Award for Song of the Year 1980s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Christopher, Johnny}}\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Song of the Year]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "BryanGaensler", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnny_Christopher"}
{"title_page": "Rolf Kemler", "text_new": "Rolf Kemler (born February 13th 1945), is a German [[molecular biology|molecular biologist]] who is currently the Emeritus Director at the [[Max Planck Institute of Immunobiology and Epigenetics]]<ref>https://www.ie-freiburg.mpg.de/5219784/2020_03_31_kemler_gairdneraward2020_eng</ref>. He has contributed significantly to the study of [[Cell junction#Anchoring_junctions|anchoring junctions]], specifically the [[cadherin]] family of proteins and was the recipient of the 2020 [[Canada Gairdner International Award]] for his work in the field.<ref name=\"pmid32234519\">{{cite journal| author=Nelson WJ| title=The Glue that Binds Us: The Hunt for the Molecular Basis for Multicellularity. | journal=Cell | year= 2020 | volume=  | issue=  | pages=  | pmid=32234519 | doi=10.1016/j.cell.2020.03.017 | pmc= | url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/elink.fcgi?dbfrom=pubmed&tool=sumsearch.org/cite&retmode=ref&cmd=prlinks&id=32234519  }} </ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n\n[[Category:German molecular biologists]]\n[[Category:Molecular biologists]]\n\n{{Germany-biologist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "Rolf Kemler (born February 13th 1945), is a German [[molecular biology|molecular biologist]] who is currently the Emeritus Director at the [[Max Planck Institute of Immunobiology and Epigenetics]]<ref>https://www.ie-freiburg.mpg.de/5219784/2020_03_31_kemler_gairdneraward2020_eng</ref>. He has contributed significantly to the study of [[Cell junction#Anchoring_junctions|anchoring junctions]], specifically the [[cadherin]] family of proteins and was the recipient of the 2020 [[Canada Gairdner International Award]] for his work in the field.<ref name=\"pmid32234519\">{{cite journal| author=Nelson WJ| title=The Glue that Binds Us: The Hunt for the Molecular Basis for Multicellularity. | journal=Cell | year= 2020 | volume=  | issue=  | pages=  | pmid=32234519 | doi=10.1016/j.cell.2020.03.017 | pmc= | url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/elink.fcgi?dbfrom=pubmed&tool=sumsearch.org/cite&retmode=ref&cmd=prlinks&id=32234519  }} </ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n\n[[Category:German molecular biologists]]\n[[Category:Molecular biologists]]\n\n{{Germany-molecular-biologist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Amir.azhieh", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolf_Kemler"}
